      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 45-year-old man is being tested for a long-standing, untreated sexually transmitted infection. The physician decides to use an older serological test that involves the detection of antibodies against Treponema pallidum. Which type of test is being used in this scenario?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5910665",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 35031,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. D) Complement fixation</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The <strong>Wasserman test </strong>is a <strong>complement fixation test </strong>used historically for the <strong>diagnosis of syphilis</strong>. It <strong>detects antibodies against Treponema pallidum </strong>by <strong>measuring the consumption of complement </strong>in the presence of <strong>antigen-antibody complexes.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Complement fixation test </strong>(CFT) detects the <strong>antibodies in patient’s serum </strong>that are <strong>capable of fixing with complements</strong>. It is almost obsolete.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Applications</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">CFT was widely used for detection of complement fixing antibodies in Rickettsia, Chlamydia, Mycoplasma infections and some viral infections, such as arboviral infections.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Complements are also used for various other serological tests such as: Treponema pallidum immobilization test for syphilis and Sabin-Feldman dye test for Toxoplasma.</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/04/screenshot-2024-03-04-160259.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"700\" height=\"423\"></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A. Agglutination test</strong>: This involves the <strong>clumping of particles or cells</strong>, not primarily used in the Wasserman test.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Precipitation test</strong>: This involves the <strong>formation of a precipitate in antigen-antibody reactions</strong>, not characteristic of the Wasserman test but characteristic of VDRL (a slide flocculation working on the same principle as precipitation), another screening &nbsp;test done for syphilis.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Neutralization test</strong>: This is used to <strong>measure the ability of antibodies to neutralize the biological effects of an antigen</strong>, not used in the Wasserman test.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The <strong>Wasserman test </strong>is a <strong>complement fixation test </strong>historically <strong>used for diagnosing syphilis by detecting antibodies against Treponema pallidum</strong>. Can <strong>detect complement-fixing antibodies </strong>in infections like <strong>Rickettsia</strong>, <strong>Chlamydia</strong>, <strong>Mycoplasma</strong>, and certain <strong>viral infections</strong>, including <strong>arboviral infections</strong>. Obsolete now.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Ref:&nbsp;</u>Apurba Sastry’s Essentials of Medical Microbiology 1/e p128, 2/e p133, Ananthanarayan 10/e p112- 113</strong></span></p>",
